<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-238-628  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 238 628.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  Feb 1990 v24 n2 p49(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fault-tolerant fiber optic networks at New York City airports.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Diamond, Sam.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A $33.5 million automated revenue-control system will be broughton-line at New York City airport parking lots in 1991, replacing asystem installed in 1970 and easing management of an $80 million ayear business while cutting revenue losses and eliminating longexit waiting lines.andP;  The contract for the project was won by NynexInformation Solutions Group, and will be fulfilled withfault-tolerant Nonstop CLX computer systems from Tandem Computersand a fiber optic local area network from Foundation Instrumentsthat will support the backbone network by allowing transactions torun in the opposite direction if a fault occurs anywhere on themain network.andP;  The new system will allow travelers to pay theirparking fees in advance with cash or credit card at automatedparking machines (APMs) situated in baggage areas and otherconvenient locations.andP;  Prepaid customers can quickly leave thelots, minimizing the number of attendant transactions and theamount of cash to be tracked manually.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Foundation Instruments Inc (products)Tandem Computers Inc. (products)NYNEX Information Solutions Group Inc. (contracts).andO;Product:   Tandem Computers Nonstop CLX (Minicomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Port Authority of New York and New JerseyAirportsEFTS.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Airport communications network by Nynex. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>